CONTEXT API:
 The Context API in React is a built-in feature that allows you to share data across multiple components without having to pass props manually through every level of the component tree.
 Itâ€™s mainly used for state management when you need to provide global data like user info, themes, or app settings.

 Why Context API?

Normally, data flows top-down through props. But if a deeply nested component needs access to some data, youâ€™d have to pass props through multiple layers â€” this is called â€œprop drilling.â€
The Context API solves this problem by creating a shared data store that any component can access directly.

STEPS:
1. Create a Context.
2. Provide the Context (Wrap Components)
3. Consume the Context  (Using useContext hook)

WHEN TO USE Context API :
Theme (dark/light mode)
User authentication info
Language/localization
App-wide settings

REDUCER IN REACT
-------------------
Redux is a powerful state management library for React applications. In normal React, when the state is small, itâ€™s easy to manage it inside individual components. But as the app grows, you need to share state between multiple components. Thatâ€™s where Redux becomes useful.

âœ… Why Redux?

To achieve centralized state management in the application
To share data between components
To get predictable state updates
To make debugging easier

âœ… Main parts of Redux
1ï¸âƒ£ Store
This is the central store that holds the entire applicationâ€™s state.
Usually, you have a single store.

2ï¸âƒ£ Actions

Simple JavaScript objects used to request state changes.
Every action has a type.

Example:

{ type: "INCREMENT" }

3ï¸âƒ£ Reducers

Functions that decide how the state should be updated.
Note: Reducers must be pure functions.

Example reducer:

const counterReducer = (state = 0, action) => {
  if(action.type === "INCREMENT"){
    return state + 1;
  }
  return state;
};

4ï¸âƒ£ Dispatch

Used to send an action to the store.

5ï¸âƒ£ Subscribe

Used to detect when the store updates
(in React we use useSelector instead).

âœ… Using Redux in React

useSelector() â†’ Read state from the store

useDispatch() â†’ Dispatch actions

ğŸ”„ Redux flow in a single sentence:

UI â†’ Action â†’ Reducer â†’ Store Update â†’ UI re-render

âœ… Example flow (Simple English)

User clicks a button (UI)

Action is dispatched â†’ { type: "ADD_TO_CART" }

The reducer checks the action and updates the state

Store saves the new state

UI updates automatically

âœ… Summary (Simple English)

Redux helps manage state in React through a central store.
When you dispatch an action, the reducer updates the state, the store saves it, and React automatically refreshes the UI with the new state.

action.payload = The data you send to the reducer when dispatching an action.

BrowserRouter:
*******************
 is a component from the react-router-dom library that enables routing in a React application.
It uses the browserâ€™s History API to keep the UI in sync with the URL.

 It acts like a wrapper for your entire app, so that routing can work properly.
You must wrap your app (or main component) inside BrowserRouter.

Routes
*********
Routes is a container that holds all your Route components.
It checks the URL and renders the component that matches the current path.

Route
*******
Route defines a single path and the component to render when that path matches.
It has two main props:

path â†’ the URL path (e.g., /about)
element â†’ the component to display


